snippet.textDisplay:
What you say about doing Star Wars reviews is emblematic of the issues with the trilogy: it is not fun discussing Star Wars anymore. Some of the Star Wars fans, despite having some very rational concerns with the trilogy, seem to want to see it burn rather than see it succeed to live another day, which makes one wonder why they talk about something so much if they no longer care about it. On the other end are equally vicious and destructive people who care more about achieving some perceived moral high ground than the movie or trilogy in question actually being good, consistent and entertaining, and they dismiss valid concerns as bigoted so that they can avoid having proper counterarguments of their own.

All that said, this is my favorite review of this film and of the trilogy as a whole that I have seen or read so far. These are the honest and unfiltered words of a fan who wanted to find something in these films and had to face facts upon its conclusion that it was, unfortunately, a failure. As someone who loves movies but does not consider themselves a "Star Wars fan," specifically, this is the kind of review I want and of which we should have way more than we do.

snippet.textDisplay:
I agree with a lot of what you're saying, but to me the Palpatine element was where the sequel trilogy finally (belatedly) got back on the rails.
I think Lucas never actually meant to make any Episodes VII--IX. The prequels plus the originals together are the story of Palpatine and Anakin Skywalker, and both of their stories ended on the Second Death Star. The Force Awakens and The Last Jedi were not part of that story, any more than Star Trek: The Next Generation was a continuation of the original Star Trek. They were just another story that happened to be set in the same universe a generation later.
Only with The Rise of Skywalker did the sequels come back into the fold. My main complaint is that Abrams shoved in a lot of stuff that he really should have been laying the groundwork for two movies before.


Here's how I reconcile it with the whole "Anakin brings balance to the Force" stuff. This might get a bit long.
I never liked the "bring balance to the Force" prophecy. Prophecies are a lazy plot device to begin with, because you can take any plot hole in your story and bung in a prophecy that said things had to happen that way. Chosen Ones likewise are a way to get out of doing the work of building a genuinely exceptional character. But OK, let's say there's a prophesied Chosen One. What has he been Chosen for? Something specific like "He contains a piece of Voldemort's soul and now the two are linked and neither can die while the other survives", I do hope. Oh... no. He's going to do something hand-wavey called "bringing balance to the Force".
And then, I don't blame them, a bunch of well-meaning fans decided that, since we know Anakin will end up killing Palpatine, that must be what "bringing balance to the Force" meant all along. Well written, George! Yay!


No, with Rise of Skywalker under our hats I think we well-meaning fans can do the same trick again and retcon the new information into the old. Here's my way to do that:
1. The Sith were always accumulating souls, from the beginning. Maybe not of Sith apprentices, but definitely of Sith masters. Each Sith apprentice becomes a Horcrux for his master, if I can once again switch fandoms for the sake of analogy.

2. This accumulation of Sith souls was how the Force was out of balance.

3. Qui-Gon knew there was to be a Chosen One who would end the Sith and bring the Force back into balance. He was right about that.

4. Anakin could have been the Chosen One if he had not turned to the Dark Side. As it was he killed Palpatine's body but didn't bring an end to the Sith soul-tower.

5. That means the real Chosen One turned out to be... well, you can figure this one out.

snippet.textDisplay:
Really? You like everything plot wise with Kylo Ren's character but you didn't like that if he was going to die, there should have been no kiss? What? Kylo Ren was doomed to die from the very beginning. That's just the path he chose, tragically, and from the moment I think he kills his Dad narratively speaking there is no way out of it but for him to die. Period. Bonus roll if he dies heroically, sure, but I guess then if you were the director he'd have just had his heroic moment with an approving smile from Rey only to die. Boo.

With the kiss, it basically does a lot of things including actually confirming that Rey does have some feelings for him, too, as boundlessly evil as he was. As many times as she had bested him in the past. THAT KISS was symbolic of not just her forgiving him, but Ben forgiving himself. Also it serves to highlight what could've been if he had simply made different (better) choices during his adolescence and especially during his training with Luke (which he had some genuine right to grieve over, in the ridiculous narrative that Rian Johnson gave us).

If JJ Abrams was allowed to direct all three, all three of these movies would have had a more cohesive fit. They didn't even have the prospective directors have a conversation with each other to try and figure out where this thing was going, they were just like "Oh well fuck it! Just make the movies, these morons will go see anything we make anyway. Who cares?" But the idea that Kylo's kiss with Rey was not warranted there, nah, it was coming just as surely as his death was and for them not to pay that off would've just been yet another missed opportunity from the writing department. It underlies everything that much better if he gets his kiss just before dying.
